{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Notably, these methods do not test the LLMs' puzzle solving capacity but rather assess their ability to encode puzzles into appropriate representations.",
    "The primary approach involves using LLMs to generate logic rules from the puzzle's natural language and subsequently solve it using a symbolic solver.",
    "Ishay et al. (2023) employ GPT-3 and GPT-4 to transform logic puzzles, such as chess puzzles, Jobs puzzle and Sudoku (rule-based/deterministic) into Answer Set Programming (ASP) formats by generating predicates and rules.",
    "They demonstrate that this method achieved significant results, with GPT-4 scoring 92% accuracy in a logic puzzles dataset Mitra and Baral (2015), compared to 7% in few-shot and 21% in zero-shot settings with the same model.",
    "They note that in few-shot settings, LLMs can generate complex programs that humans can easily refine and correct in case of code errors."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Ishay et al. (2023) employ GPT-3 and GPT-4 to transform logic puzzles, such as chess puzzles, Jobs puzzle and Sudoku (rule-based/deterministic) into Answer Set Programming (ASP) formats by generating predicates and rules.",
    "They demonstrate that this method achieved significant results, with GPT-4 scoring 92% accuracy in a logic puzzles dataset Mitra and Baral (2015), compared to 7% in few-shot and 21% in zero-shot settings with the same model."
  ]
